= [[Marie Royce|Marie Porter]]\n| education = [[California State University, Fullerton]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])\n}}\n'''Edward Randall Royce''' (born October 12, 1951) is an American politician serving as a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[California]] since 1993. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], Royce became Chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs]] in 2013. He previously served as a member of the [[California Senate]] from 1982 to 1993.\n\nHe was reelected to his seat in [[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2016|2016]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/election2016-734760-election-results.html|title=2016 Election results: U.S. Senate, House and California legislature|work=The Orange County Register|accessdate=2017-03-26}}</ref> having spent over $3.5 million on his campaign.<ref name=\"opensecrets1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/elections.php?cycle=Career&cid=N00008264&type=I|title=Rep. Ed Royce: Campaign Finance/Money - Elections - Representative Career|website=opensecrets.org|accessdate=2017-03-26}}</ref> On January 8, 2018, Royce announced that he will retire from [[United States Congress|Congress]] at the end of his current term and not run for reelection in [[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2018|2018]].<ref name=@RepEdRoyce>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RepEdRoyce/status/950494272234688512|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRoyce was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. He graduated from [[Katella High School]] in [[Anaheim, California]]. He earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[Accounting]] and [[Finance]] in 1977 from [[California State University, Fullerton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.calstate.edu/impact-of-the-csu/government/federal-relations/Pages/csu-alumni.aspx|title=CSU Alumni|website=www2.calstate.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-07}}</ref> \n\n==Early career==\nRoyce was a business owner and [[corporate tax]] manager for a [[Portland cement]] company before becoming a [[California State Senate|California State Senator]] in 1983, serving in that post until his election to the U.S. House of Representatives.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\nAfter redistricting following the [[1990 United States Census]], incumbent Republican U.S. Representative [[William Dannemeyer]] decided to retire and run for the [[United States Senate election in California, 1992|1992 U.S. Senate election]]. Royce won the Republican primary for what was then [[California's 39th congressional district]], which included most of northern Orange County and southern Los Angeles County.\n\nHe defeated Democrat Molly McClanahan in the general election with 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=27873|title=CA District 39 Race|date=November 3, 1992|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=2017-04-03}}</ref>\n\nHe won re-election to the 39th district four more times with at least 63% of the vote. After redistricting after the [[2000 United States Census]], his district was renumbered the 40th and cut back to northern Orange County. He won re-election from this district five more times with at least 63% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=812|title=Candidate - Edward R. Royce|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=2017-04-03}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012#District 39}}\nAfter redistricting, Royce's home in Fullerton was drawn into the 39th district. That district had previously been the 42nd District, represented by fellow Republican [[Gary Miller]]. Although it was geographically more Miller's district than Royce's, Royce would have been favored in a primary battle with Miller\u2013which would have been the real contest in this heavily Republican district. Ultimately, Miller opted to move to the neighboring 31st District,<ref>Trygstad, Kyle. [http://www.rollcall.com/news/Gary-Miller-Switching-Districts-California-211467-1.html Gary Miller Switches California Districts to Avoid Battle With Ed Royce]. ''[[Roll Call]]'', 2012-01-12.</ref> effectively handing the seat to Royce.\n\nRoyce defeated Jay Chen in the general election.<ref name=\"Royce VoteSmart\">{{cite web|title=Representative Edward 'Ed' R. Royce's Political Positions|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/26772/ed-royce/#.UGZJxRh9ky4|work=VoteSmart|publisher=VoteSmart|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n\nIn 2012 he was endorsed by 11 of 14 Republicans<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/international/269661-rep-royce-selected-as-new-chairman-of-house-foreign-affairs-committee|title=Rep. Royce selected as new chairman of House Foreign Affairs committee|last=Strauss|first=Daniel|date=2012-11-27|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-08-07|language=en}}</ref> as chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Foreign Affairs Committee]] and has served as chairman since January 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2012/12/16/rep-ed-royce-the-new-house-foreign-affairs-chairman/|title=Rep. Ed Royce: The new House Foreign Affairs chairman|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-08-07}}</ref>\n\nRoyce voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[File:U.S. House Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman Ed Royce and wife Marie meet Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen at the Presidential Office in Taipei, Taiwan in 2016 \u81fa\u7063\u7e3d\u7d71\u8521\u82f1\u6587\u8207\u7f8e\u570b\u773e\u8b70\u9662\u5916\u4ea4\u59d4\u54e1\u6703\u4e3b\u5e2d\u7f85\u4f0a\u65af\u592b\u5a66.jpg|thumb|U.S. House Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman Ed Royce and wife [[Marie Royce|Marie]] meet [[Taiwanese President]] [[Tsai Ing-wen]] at the [[Presidential Office Building, Taiwan|Presidential Office]] in [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]] in 2016]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets, Insurance and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance|Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]], Chair'''\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Human Rights Caucus\n* Congressional Military Family Caucus\n* Congressional Internet Caucus\n* House Recycling Caucus\n* Victim\u2019s Rights Caucus\n* International Conservation Caucus\n* Congressional Caucus on Korea\n* Congressional Caucus on India and Indian Americans\n* Congressional Caucus on Vietnam\n* Taiwan Caucus\n* U.S. Philippines Friendship Caucus\n* Congressional Cement Caucus\n* Climate Solutions Caucus\n* [[House Baltic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n* Co-Chair [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nSituated in a district that supported [[Hillary Clinton]] in the 2016 Presidential election by a margin of eight points,<ref name=\"California Secretary of State\">{{cite web|title=Supplement to the Statement of the Vote Counties by Congressional Districts for President|url=http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/sov/2016-general/ssov/pres-by-congress.pdf|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> Royce was widely viewed as one of the most vulnerable members of Congress.<ref>{{cite web|title=California could flip the House, and these 13 races will make the difference|url=http://www.latimes.com/projects/la-pol-ca-california-congressional-race-rankings/|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> As of December 2017, polling in the 39th District showed a 36% approval rating for Royce and a 60% disapproval rating for [[President Trump]].<ref name=\"Public Policy Polling\">{{cite web|title= Congressional Republicans Vulnerable in Upcoming Re-Elections|url=http://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/2c7561_ae1db5df7001481bbfc5dded05778b71.pdf|publisher=Public Policy Polling|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> Additionally, the data showed that a large majority of voters disapproved of Royce's public support and vote in favor of the Republican [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Public Policy Polling\"/> Acknowledging the difficult campaign ahead and the end of his six-year term as Chairman of the [[House Foreign Relations Committee]],<ref name=\"Orange County Register\">{{cite web|title=Ed Royce, Longtime Orange County Congressman, Plans to Leave Congress|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2018/01/08/ed-royce-longtime-o-c-congressman-plans-to-retire/|publisher=Orange County Register|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> Royce decided to announce his retirement and decision to not run for reelection in 2018 via [[Twitter]] on January 8, 2018.<ref name=@RepEdRoyce>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RepEdRoyce/status/950494272234688512|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> Thirty minutes following his announcement, [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] formally nominated Royce's wife [[Marie Royce]] to be [[Assistant Secretary of State for Educational and Cultural Affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|title=California Republican Rep. Ed Royce won't seek reelection, creating bigger opening for Democrats|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-ed-royce-retirement-20180108-story.html|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> In retiring, Royce joined the \"casualty list\" of 36 Republican members of the 115th Congress who have left or announced their intention to leave the [[House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"United States House of Representatives Press Gallery\">{{cite web|title=Casualty List|url=https://pressgallery.house.gov/member-data/casualty-list|publisher=United States House of Representatives|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and PACs==\n{{BLP sources section|date=April 2017}}\nRoyce is one of 14 House Republicans from California. He has voted with his party in 97% of votes so far in the current session of Congress and voted in line with President Trump's position in 92.9% of the votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/edward-r-royce|title=Tracking Edward R. Royce In The Age Of Trump|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron|date=2017-01-30|accessdate=2017-02-18|newspaper=FiveThirtyEight}}</ref> Despite this, for the [[114th United States Congress]], Royce was ranked as the 27th most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives (and the most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from California) in the Bipartisan Index created by [[The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] that ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party).<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> Over his career, Royce has received nearly $7 million from PACs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cycle=Career&cid=N00008264|title=Rep. Ed Royce: Campaign Finance/Money - Summary|website=opensecrets.org|language=en|accessdate=2017-03-26}}</ref>  In the 2016 race, he raised over $4.2 million and spent over $3.5 million.<ref name=\"opensecrets1\"/>\n\nHis campaign committee received funds from Northwest Excavating, [[Deutsche Bank]], [[Morgan Stanley]] and NorPac. The Sunlight Foundation gave Royce's web site a 24 percent rating for transparency,<ref>[http://www.sunlightlabs.com/research/sites/results/results.php?cid=N00008264 Congressional Web Site Investigation Project: Sunlight Foundation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927070721/http://www.sunlightlabs.com/research/sites/results/results.php?cid=N00008264|date=September 27, 2007}}</ref> with 40 percent being considered a passing score. Royce's website highlights support from [[conservative]] groups such as [[60 Plus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unitedseniors.org/NewsReleases.cfm|title=Archived copy|accessdate=2007-08-13|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211131919/http://www.unitedseniors.org/NewsReleases.cfm|archivedate=2014-12-11}}</ref>  and business organizations such as the [[National Taxpayers Union]] and [[Citizens Against Government Waste]]. He received praise from the American Share Holders Association, Citizens for a Sound Economy, and the Small Business Survival Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edroyce.com/about|title=Royce|website=Edroyce.com|accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the 113th Congress, the Washington Post named Royce as one of the \u201c10 most effective lawmakers in the U.S. Congress\u201d, citing his authorship of the Global Anti-Poaching Act (H.R. 2494) and the Hizballah International Financing Prevention Act of 2015 (H.R. 2297).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2015/12/28/these-are-the-top-10-most-effective-lawmakers-in-the-u-s-congress/|title=These are the 10 most effective lawmakers in the U.S. Congress|last=Volden|first=Craig|date=2015-12-28|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-05-29|last2=Wiseman|first2=Alan|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic policy===\nRoyce's voting record, his scores on VoteMatch, and ratings by the [[Cato Institute]] indicate mixed or moderate positions on [[free trade]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=\"OnTheIssues\"/> [[privatization]] of [[social security]], campaign finance,<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> and tax reform.<ref name=\"OnTheIssues\"/>\n\n==== Abortion ====\n\nRoyce is pro-life.<ref name=\"Wisckol9117\">{{cite web|last1=Wisckol|first1=Martin|title=Rep. Ed Royce rebukes Trump on Arpaio pardon|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2017/09/01/rep-ed-royce-rebukes-trump-on-arpaio-pardon/|website=Orange County Register|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Banking deregulation, business issues====\nOne of Royce's early signature issues was banking deregulation. He has sponsored legislation on [[fiscal policy|tax policy]], small businesses, and credit. Many of his biggest campaign contributors have been banks: his five top contributors in 2006 were Credit Union National Assn, Irvine Co., Wells Fargo, Orange County Teachers Fed Credit Union, and GUS plc. He is among the representatives receiving the largest percentage of their campaign contributions from the banking industry.<ref>[http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2008/10/races-to-watch-ix-wall-streets.html Races to Watch IX: Wall Street\u2019s Favorite Candidates \u2013 OpenSecrets Blog], OpenSecrets.org; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2013, Royce introduced the [[Credit Union Share Insurance Fund Parity Act (H.R. 3468; 113th Congress)]] into the House.<ref name=\"3468sum\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 3468 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3468|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref> The bill would expand federal deposit insurance to include [[Interest on Lawyer Trust Accounts]] (IOLTAs) and similar escrow accounts housed within credit unions.<ref name=\"cbo3468\">{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 3468|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45007|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Cannabis ====\n\nRoyce has a \"C\" rating from [[NORML]] regarding his voting record on [[cannabis]]-related matters. He voted against allowing veterans access to [[medical marijuana]], if legal in their state, per their Veterans Health Administration doctor's recommendation.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=California Scorecard - NORML.org - Working to Reform Marijuana Laws|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/california|website=norml.org|accessdate=22 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==== Guns ====\n\nRoyce has a \"A\" rating from the [[National Rifle Association]] regarding his voting record on [[gun]]-related matters.<ref name=\"Wisckol9117\"/>\n\nIn the wake of the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Royce posted on Facebook that \"We need to defeat the terrorists and make it our top national security priority to prevail in the war against radical [[Islamic extremism]].\" He did not mention the families or gun laws.<ref name=\"Berkowitz61616\">{{cite web|last1=Berkowitz|first1=Bonnie|last2=Cai|first2=Weiyi|last3=Lu|first3=Denise|last4=Gamio|first4=Lazaro|title=Everything lawmakers said (and didn't say) after the Orlando mass shooting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/national/how-lawmakers-responded-to-the-orlando-mass-shooting/|website=Washington Post|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Taxes and budgets====\nHe has received 14 \"Taxpayer Friend Awards\" from the National Taxpayers' Union.<ref>[http://blog.ntu.org/main/post.php?post_id=3403 Government Bytes: The Official Blog of National Taxpayers Union], blog.ntu.org; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> Royce opposes funding for the [[Overseas Private Investment Corporation]] (OPIC).<ref>[http://www.progress.org/banneker/cwkasi.htm Corporate Welfare OPIC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609013649/http://www.progress.org/banneker/cwkasi.htm |date=2007-06-09 }}, progress.org; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> Royce has posited that these overseas investments expose taxpayers to a serious potential liability, just like the S&L crisis did.<ref>[http://www.reason.com/news/show/30166.html Corporate Welfare Reform], reason.com; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref>\n\n====Social issues and Islam====\nRoyce is a [[social conservative]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">[http://www.issues2000.org/CA/Ed_Royce_HouseMatch.htm Ed Royce profile], issues2000.org; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> having voted against [[same-sex marriage]] and [[LGBT adoption in the United States|gay adoption]], and in favor of [[school prayer]] and [[school voucher]]s.<ref name=\"OnTheIssues\">[http://www.ontheissues.org/CA/Ed_Royce.htm Ed Royce on the Issues], ontheissues.org; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> He has a 92 percent rating from the [[Christian Coalition of America|Christian Coalition]] in terms of his voting record on families and children.<ref name=\"OnTheIssues\"/> He is [[pro-life]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> his votes resulting in [[NARAL]]'s most consistent possible score.<ref name=\"OnTheIssues\"/> He has voted in favor of a [[Flag burning amendment|constitutional amendment forbidding flag burning]], and in favor of making the [[USA PATRIOT Act]] permanent. He has an A rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]].<ref name=\"OnTheIssues\"/>\n\nRoyce was criticized for attending a rally in his home county, in which members of anti-Muslim groups chanted at Muslim-American families attending Islamic charity event that they should \"go home.\" Royce replied that the anti-Muslim chants were done by provocateurs, not the main group of protesters. He disavowed the chants, saying \"those remarks and conduct were disrespectful and offensive\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/richard-adams-blog/2011/mar/03/orange-county-protest-islam|title=The ugly face of Islamophobia in Orange County, California|publisher=[[The Guardian|Guardian]]|date=2011-03-03|first=Richard|last=Adams|accessdate=2011-03-03|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/blog-post/2011/03/anti-muslim_rallies_spark_ange.html|title=Anti-Muslim videos spark anger; pro-Muslim rally planned for March 6 (#mar6)|publisher=Washington Post|first=Melissa|last=Bell|accessdate=2011-03-04}}</ref> Royce supports President Trump's [[Executive Order 13769]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/paul-ryan-trumps-refugee-ban-does-not-target-muslims/2017/01/28/e0cf1fe4-e56e-11e6-a547-5fb9411d332c_story.html?tid=pm_pop |title=The Washington Post |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\n====Victims' rights====\n<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phinney|first1=David|title=Clinton Signs O.C.-Born Bill Outlawing Stalking|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-24/news/mn-47044_1_bill-signing|accessdate=April 12, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 24, 1996}}</ref> Royce sponsored anti-stalking legislation signed into law by President Bill Clinton, which was based on legislation Royce had authored as a California State Senator. In 2003, he sponsored another bill as US representative related to victims.<ref>[http://www.stalkingalert.com/lalawyer.htm Royce legislation], stalkingalert.com; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref>\n\n====Health Care====\nOn May 4, 2017, he voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and pass the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/04/health-care-vote-puts-pressure-dozens-vulnerable-gop-reps/101297824/|title=Health care vote puts pressure on dozens of vulnerable GOP reps|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Donald Trump's tax returns====\nIn February 2017, he voted against a resolution that would have directed the House to request 10 years of Trump's tax returns, which would then have been reviewed by the House Ways and Means Committee in a closed session.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indy100.com/article/republican-vote-donald-trump-tax-president-united-states-229-185-congress-7603851|title=These are all the Republicans who don\u2019t want you to see Donald Trump\u2019s tax returns|date=2017-02-28|work=indy100|accessdate=2017-03-01}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\nIn [[foreign policy]], Royce's voting record has earned a 0% rating from the peace organization [[Peace Action|SANE]].<ref name=\"OnTheIssues\"/> In 2011, Royce voted against the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] as part of a controversial provision that allows the government and the military to indefinitely detain American citizens and others without trial.<ref>{{cite web|author=Connor Adams Sheets|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/ndaa-bill-how-did-your-congress-member-vote-384362?page=1|title=NDAA Bill: How Did Your Congress Member Vote?|website=Ibtimes.com|date=2011-10-27|accessdate=2017-04-03}}</ref>\n\n====Iran nuclear agreement ====\nIn 2016, Royce criticized the Iran nuclear agreement and Obama administration harshly, saying the deal was \"a financial windfall\u201d for Iran and a \"a cash bonanza, a boost to its international standing, and a lighted path toward nuclear weapons.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/iran-nuclear-talks/house-gop-panel-grill-john-kerry-iran-deal-n399621|title=House GOP Panel Grills John Kerry on Iran Nuclear Deal|work=NBC News|access-date=2017-10-12|language=en}}</ref> He called for re-introducing sanctions on Iran.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-nuclear-usa-sanctions-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-house-to-vote-on-iran-sanctions-act-renewal-as-soon-as-november-idUSKCN12P2GG|title=Exclusive: U.S. House to vote on Iran Sanctions Act renewal as soon as November|last=|first=|date=2016|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref> Later, in 2017, after Donald Trump had become President, Royce said that he was in favor of staying in the Iran nuclear agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/09/19/politics/ed-royce-foreign-affairs-iran-nuclear/index.html|title=Royce suggests US should stay in Iran deal|last=CNN|first=Eli Watkins,|work=CNN|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/354898-foreign-affairs-chairman-us-should-stay-in-iran-deal-but-enforce-the-hell-out|title=House Foreign Affairs chairman: US should stay in Iran deal, but 'enforce the hell' out of it|last=Kheel|first=Rebecca|date=2017-10-11|work=TheHill|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>\n\n====North Korea====\n[[File:Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich and Congressman Jay Kim (R-Calif.) face North Korea from the Joint Security Area (JSA) A1501-SCN-97-0027-003.jpg|thumb|Congressmen Royce, [[Jay Kim]] and House Speaker [[Newt Gingrich]] face [[North Korea]] from the [[Joint Security Area]] in 1997]]\nRoyce serves as a senior member of the Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Asia. He and has been especially involved in policy regarding North Korea, working on issues such as human rights, counterfeiting of U.S. currency, nuclear proliferation,<ref>\"Kim the Counterfeiter,\" by Ed Royce, March 10, 2007, https://www.wsj.com</ref> and stopping repatriation of refugees.<ref>[http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=2847 Green Light on U.S. Legislation to Help North Korean Refugees in China], dailynk.com; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> Royce's district includes [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], which has a large population of Korean immigrants.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} During a slow-rolling crisis in 2017 between the US and North Korea, Royce introduced legislation expanding sanctions against North Korea and requiring that its designation as a state sponsor of terror be reinstated.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dagyum Ji |url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/03/new-north-korea-sanctions-bill-introduced-to-u-s-house-of-representatives/ |title=New North Korea sanctions bill introduced to U.S. House of Representatives |newspaper=North Korea News |date=2017-03-22 |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\n====Conflicts in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya, and Yemen====\nRoyce was a supporter of the US wars in Iraq and Afghanistan. In 2002, he voted in favor of authorizing [[U.S. President|President]] [[George W. Bush]] to use force in Iraq.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://www.unitedforpeace.org/article.php?list=type&type=114 Legislative Resources] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814191610/http://www.unitedforpeace.org/article.php?list=type&type=114 |date=2007-08-14 }}, unitedforpeace.org; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> In 2003, he voted yes on an emergency appropriation of $78 billion for the [[Iraq War|wars in Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"OnTheIssues\"/> From 2003-06, he voted in favor of the annual supplemental spending bill to continue funding for the Iraq war.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>[http://vcnv.org/house-of-representative-voting-records January 2007 \u2013 House Of Representative Voting Records] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814195156/http://vcnv.org/house-of-representative-voting-records |date=2007-08-14 }}, Voices for Creative Nonviolence CIV website; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> In 2005, he voted against Amendment 214 to HR 1815, which called on Bush to develop a plan for withdrawing U.S. troops from Iraq; in favor of Amendment 488 to HR 2601 to keep troops in Iraq; and in favor of HR 612 opposing a timetable for withdrawal of troops from Iraq.<ref>[http://www.peace-action.org/ Profile], peace-action.org; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> In 2006, he voted for HR 861, a resolution labeling the war in Iraq as part of a [[war on terror|global war against terrorism]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nHe has supported U.S. broadcasting efforts in Asia, initiating legislation to create [[Radio Free Asia]] and [[Radio Free Afghanistan]] on the model of [[Radio Free Europe]]/[[Radio Liberty]].<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/releases/2007/01/456-300107.asp Radio Free Afghanistan Celebrates Five Years Of Broadcasting], Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty; accessed April 3, 2017.</ref> Royce had a mixed voting record on the 2011 [[2011 military intervention in Libya|US involvement in Libya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=25382195&category=views&id=743961076769|title=Ed Royce - Libya|website=Thepoliticalguide.com|accessdate=2017-04-03}}</ref> In 2015, he supported the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2015/03/27/saudi-arabia-gets-bipartisan-backing-for-yemen-airstrikes|title=Saudi Arabia Gets Bipartisan Backing for Yemen Airstrikes|work=USNews.com|date=March 27, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328004338/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2015/03/27/saudi-arabia-gets-bipartisan-backing-for-yemen-airstrikes|archivedate=2015-03-28}}</ref>\n\n====Africa====\nRoyce was formerly chair of the Africa Subcommittee. He co-led, with [[Colin Powell]], a delegation to observe [[Nigeria]]'s [[Nigerian presidential election, 1999|historic elections in 1999]] and led a delegation to [[Darfur]] to bring attention to the ongoing [[Darfur genocide|genocide]] in 2005 and led efforts in the House to bring [[Charles Taylor (Liberia)|Charles Taylor]], the former [[President of Liberia]], to stand trial before the Special Court of [[Sierra Leone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/05/opinion/05royce.html|title=Bring Charles Taylor to Justice|first=Ed|last=Royce|date=May 5, 2005|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justiceinitiative.org/db/resource2?res_id%3D103047|title=Royce, Bipartisan Group of Lawmakers Call for Charles Taylor to be Brought to Justice|accessdate=October 9, 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061120184300/http://www.justiceinitiative.org/db/resource2?res_id=103047|archivedate=November 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn April 26, 2013, Royce introduced the [[North Korea Sanctions Enforcement Act of 2013 (H.R. 1771; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would increase U.S. sanctions on [[North Korea]].<ref name=\"1771sum\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 1771 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1771|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> Royce said that \"by shutting down North Korea's illicit activities, we deprive the Kim regime of the money he needs to pay his generals and to conduct nuclear weapons research.\"<ref name=\"MarcosPasses\">{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=House passes bill to toughen North Korea sanctions|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/213553-house-passes-bill-to-toughen-north-korea-sanctions|accessdate=July 30, 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=July 28, 2014}}</ref> Royce also argued that \"North Korea is undoubtedly one of the most significant security threats that we here face and our allies face.\"<ref name=\"MarcosPasses\"/>\n\nOn June 27, 2013, Royce introduced the [[Electrify Africa Act of 2013 (H.R. 2548; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[President of the United States|President]] to establish a multiyear strategy to assist countries in [[sub-Saharan Africa]] develop an appropriate mix of power solutions to provide sufficient [[electricity]] access to people living in rural and urban areas in order to alleviate [[poverty]] and drive economic growth.<ref name=\"2548sum\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 2548 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/2548|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2013, Royce introduced the [[Taiwan Relations Act Affirmation and Naval Vessel Transfer Act of 2014 (H.R. 3470; 113th Congress)]] into the House.<ref name=\"3470sum\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 3470 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3470|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> The bill would allow the sale of several [[Oliver Hazard Perry-class frigate]]s to [[Mexico]], [[Thailand]], and [[Taiwan]].<ref name=\"3470sum\"/> Four naval vessels would be sold to Taiwan for about $10 million each.<ref name=\"3470cbo\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 3470 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/sites/default/files/cbofiles/attachments/hr3470.pdf|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=April 5, 2014}}</ref> Mexico and Thailand would each receive two vessels as a grant.<ref name=\"3470sum\"/> Royce argued in favor of the bill saying that \"these ships would bolster Taiwan's defense.\"<ref name=\"Houseapproves7\">{{cite news|last=Marcos|first=Cristina|title=House approves sale of missile frigates to Taiwan|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/votes/202884-house-approves-sale-of-missile-frigates-to-taiwan|accessdate=April 8, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=April 7, 2014}}</ref> Royce also said that \"these transfers help support the priorities of the U.S. Navy while strengthening the capability of allies and our close partners to meet our share maritime security objectives.\"<ref name=\"Houseapproves7\"/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* [[Order of Brilliant Star]] with Grand Cordon \u2013 Taiwan (Republic of China) <ref>{{cite news|last1=Huang|first1=Kelven|last2=Hou|first2=Elaine|title=President confers medal on U.S. congressman for supporting Taiwan|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201503130037.aspx|accessdate=March 14, 2015|agency=Central News Agency|date=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Order of Brilliant Star]] with Special Grand Cordon \u2013 Taiwan (Republic of China)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yeh|first1=Sophia|last2=Low|first2=Y. F.|title=President confers medal on U.S. Congressman Ed Royce|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201709010013.aspx|accessdate=1 September 2017|agency=Central News Agency|date=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRoyce is married to [[Marie Therese Porter]], a businesswoman, former Professor at [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona]], and the [[Assistant Secretary of State for Educational and Cultural Affairs]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://royce.house.gov/ Congressman Ed Royce] official U.S. House website\n* [https://edroyce.com/ Ed Royce for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ed_Royce_%5BR-39%5D|Ed Royce}}\n* {{C-SPAN|edwardroyce}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ca-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John G. Schmitz|John Schmitz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[California State Senate|California Senate]]<br>from the [[California's 32nd State Senate district|32nd]] district|years=1982\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rob Hurtt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William E. Dannemeyer|William Dannemeyer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from California|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[California's 39th congressional district]]|years=1993\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Linda S\u00e1nchez]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jerry Lewis (California politician)|Jerry Lewis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from California|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[California's 40th congressional district]]|years=2003\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucille Roybal-Allard]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Linda S\u00e1nchez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from California|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[California's 39th congressional district]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|House Foreign Affairs Committee]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lucille Roybal-Allard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=42nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bobby Rush]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseChairs}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{US House Foreign Affairs chairs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Royce, Ed}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:California State University, Fullerton alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from California]]\n[[Category:People from Fullerton, California]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Brilliant Star]]\n[[Category:Republican Party membe